    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n5637" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κυνέη</span></b> : properly ‘dog - skin,’
          a soldier's <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">cap</span>, generally of leather, <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ταυρείη,</span>
          <i><span class="en">Il. 10.257</span></i>; <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">
            κτιδέη</span>, <i><span class="en">Il. 10.335</span></i>; also
          mounted with metal, <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">χαλκήρης,
            χαλκοπάρῃος</span>, and <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">πάγχαλκος</span>, <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">helmet</span>, <i><span class="en">Od. 18.378</span></i>; the <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">κυνέη αἰγείη</span>
          was a goat - skin cap for country wear (like that of the oarsmen in
          cut No. 38), <i><span class="en">Od. 24.231</span></i>
          <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">; Ἄιδος</span>, the cap of Hades, rendered
          the wearer invisible, <i><span class="en">Il. 5.845</span></i>. 
        </div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
